{"type":"item.completed","item":{"id":"item_28","type":"agent_message","text":"Human intervention needed\n\nThe automated job failed for `xml-apis:xml-apis:1.2.01`. Preserved work is available on `https://github.com/oracle/graalvm-reachability-metadata/tree/ai%2Fvjovanov%2Fhuman-intervention%2Fissue-2574-fails-java-run-xml-apis-xml-apis-1.2.01-f951f49b`.\n\nThe run first reproduced the Java test failure: `Xml_apisTest.versionClassReportsXmlCommonsIdentity()` expected the reported version to contain `1.0`, but the library reports `1.2.01` (`human-intervention-logs/xml-apis:xml-apis:1.2.01/gradle-test/gradle-test-2026-05-05T03-25-59-082928Z.log`). After that, the automation appears to have been blocked in artifact resolution / metadata generation: `:generateMetadata` failed with `Failed to resolve JAR for xml-apis:xml-apis:1.2.01` (`human-intervention-logs/xml-apis:xml-apis:1.2.01/native-test-verify/cycle-0-generateMetadata-2026-05-05T03-27-44-343004Z.log`), and the metrics ended with `status: failure`, `generated_loc: 0`, `test_file: None`, and `metadata_file: None` (`stats/xml-apis/xml-apis/1.2.01/execution-metrics.json`). Additional build output also shows `No eligible artifacts found on the classpath for xml-apis:xml-apis:1.2.01`, while the native test classpath contains `xerces/xmlParserAPIs/2.6.2.jar`, which strongly suggests Maven relocation handling is the real blocker rather than only the test assertion (`build/tests/xml-apis:xml-apis:1.2.01/afa9416ff9df0fcd594a002264a8ae56.out`, `build/tests/xml-apis:xml-apis:1.2.01/e89d7b2000701eec2ccda3cd6b7b60c5.out`, and `human-intervention-logs/xml-apis:xml-apis:1.2.01/metadata-fix/codex.log`).\n\nPlease inspect:\n- `human-intervention-logs/xml-apis:xml-apis:1.2.01/gradle-test/gradle-test-2026-05-05T03-25-59-082928Z.log`\n- `human-intervention-logs/xml-apis:xml-apis:1.2.01/native-test-verify/cycle-0-generateMetadata-2026-05-05T03-27-44-343004Z.log`\n- `human-intervention-logs/xml-apis:xml-apis:1.2.01/metadata-fix/codex.